# Convert ProsperRating, LoanStatus, and EmploymentStatus into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                    'EmploymentStatus': ['Not available', 'Not employed', 'Part-time', 'Full-time',
                                         'Self-employed', 'Employed', 'Retired', 'Other']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loan[var] = loan[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature(s) of interest is to look at the determinants that affects a borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for a loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that Loan Amount and Prosper Rating (Alpha) will have the strongest effect on a borrower's annual percentage rate (APR): the larger the Loan Amount and the better the Prosper Rating, the lower the APR. I also think that term, stated monthly income, employment status, is borrower a home owner and current in group will have effects on the APR.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: BorrowerAPR.

In [11]:

plt.xlabel('Borrower APR')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Distribution of Borrower APR')
plt.show;

The borrower APR distribution appears to be multimodal with some peaks around 0.1, 0.2 and 0.3. Most curiously the largest peak falls right between 0.3 and 0.4.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of borrowers APR looks multimodal with the highest peak between 0.3 and 0.4. Most of the values are at the range of 0.05 and 0.4. No need for any transformation as there are no unusual points.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distributions of stated monthly income is highly skewed to the right with most monthly incomes being less than 30k. No need for any transformation as there are no unusual distributions.

The matrix chart shows that there is a negative correlation between BorrowerAPR and LoanOriginalAmount. This indicates that the higher the LoanOriginalAmount, the lower the BorrowerAPR.

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [20, 20])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loan, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'StatedMonthlyIncome'], 
                x_vars = categoric_vars, size = 3, aspect = 1.5)
g.map(boxgrid);

Multivariate Exploration¶

From poor to better ratings, borrowers with ratings of HR have a high APR with the lowest amount in terms of loan amount. This is followed by E, D, C, B, A and AA respectively. This is true because borrowers with poor ratings tend to have high interest rate or APR with little accessibility to loan facilities where as borrowers with better ratings tend to have low interest rate or APR with better accessibility to loan facilities.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I further examined the borrower APR against loan amount by looking at the effect of the Prosper rating. This showed that with better Prosper ratings from HR through to AA, the relationship between borrower APR and loan amount changes from negative to slightly positive. I further looked the rating and term effects on loan amount which showed that as and when the ratings improved, the loan amount amongst all the categories of term increases significantly.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

An interesting interaction is that the borrower APR and loan amount are negatively related when the Prosper ratings are from HR to B, but the relationship changes to a positive one when the ratings are A and AA.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, there is a negative correlation between Borrower APR and Loan Original Amount. There is also a negative relationship between borrower APR and Prosper Rating (Alpha). However, the borrower APR decrease with the increase of borrow term for borrowers with HR-C raings. But for borrowers with B-AA ratings, the APR increase with the increase of borrow term. The feature 'IsBorrowerHomeowner' and 'CurrentlyInGroup' do not really have an impact on the correlation between Borrower APR and Loan Amount. However, borrowers who are home owners tend to have better ratings than those who are not home owners.
